It's not just handy for scripts, I think it's imperative in scripts where you want to go in and out of a lot of directories.<p><pre><code>  for i in foo bar baz; do
     cd $i;
     #... do something
     cd ..;
  done;
</code></pre>
if "bar" doesn't exist, your cd .. will throw you off your original directory, whereas<p><pre><code>  for i in foo bar baz; do
     pushd $i;
     #... do something
     popd;
  done;
</code></pre>
you'll be guaranteed that after "popd" you're back in the right place to start a new iteration.
